   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary53.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date>Monday. 31.</date>
            </dateline>
            <p>
               <time>The morning</time> was <name key="Negetive" type="Weather">raw and chilly</name> - such as we have in September. <name type="Weather">Then the sun came out</name> about <time>ten o'clock</time> and was <name type="Weather">very hot</name>
               <time>until evening</time>, when it became <name type="weather">chilly</name>. Whisky has been ordered to be served to the men, an <objectName key="Drink">ounce</objectName> in the morning I had
               determined to make application for a commission in <orgName role="Army">the regular army</orgName>, &amp; got a
               recommendation from <persName key="Thomas Bell"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper072">Lt. Col. Bell.</persName> I went over to <persName key="Jesse Reno"
                         role="Soldeir"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper086"
                         type="real">Gen Reno</persName>. He and <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008">Gen Burnside</persName>
               both advised me to hold on to my rank here, as <orgName key="Military">the army</orgName> would be reorganized,
               and Captains would receive commissions to recruit companies: that I could not
               get a higher rank than 2nd Lieut &amp; would have to rise from it. <persName key="John Morris"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper057"
                         type="real">Morris </persName>&amp;
               I rode out about a half mile, where <persName key="Thomas Williams"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper079">Capt. Williamson</persName> was building a <objectName key="Building">fort</objectName>. This
               is large to contain 8 acres, an <objectName key="Building">enclosed fort</objectName>, &amp; is about a half mile from
               <placeName role="River"
                          key="Trent River"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl083">the Trent</placeName>. Another is to be built 3/4 of a mile further toward <placeName role="River"
                          cert="unknown"
                          key="Neuse River"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl058">the Neuse<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName>, &amp;
               about a half mile from it. We had dress parade <time>this evening</time> &amp; <persName key="George Shorkley"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper002">Lt. Shorkley</persName>
               acted as adjutant, <persName key="Daniel Bible"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper022"
                         type="real">Bible</persName> being sick. Since last night, everything has moved
               with an unusual.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary53.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date>Tuesday April 1. 1862.</date>
            </dateline>
            <p>The day was <name type="Weather">hot</name>, the sun making it so - but <name type="Weather">the air would at times feel chilly</name>.
               I was quite unwell during the forenoon, weakened down by my cold and diarrhoea.
               After dinner owing to some startling rumors I was induced to [?] over to <placeName role="City / town"
                          cert="high"
                          key="New Berne"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl059">New Berne<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName>. The [?] was as still as death, but the quiet work going on was amazing.
               <objectName key="Equipment">Artillery</objectName> was being hauled out back of town: the <orgName role="Military">57th N.Y.</orgName> &amp; <orgName role="Military">11th Conn.</orgName>
               sent to work on the <objectName key="Building">fort</objectName>. Our <orgName key="Army">pickets</orgName> had been attacked last night one killed -
               <persName role="Soldier">one rebel</persName> killed &amp; a deserter came in, who gave the information, that 5000
               <orgName role="Military">rebels</orgName> were <placeName role="Next to Kingston"
                          key="Kingston"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl048">five miles this side of Kingston</placeName>, and 25,000 in <placeName role="Town"
                          key="Kingston"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl048">Kingston</placeName> advancing
               this way, under command of <persName key="Robert Ransom"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper068"
                         type="real">Gen. Ransom</persName>, an old West Pointer, well known to our
               Generals, and said to be a man of considerable dash. 
               <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary54.jpg"/>
               <fw>April 1 continued.</fw> The [?] [?] was sent to <placeName role="Base"
                          cert="unknown"
                          key="Hatteras Light House"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl046">Hatteras<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName> last night at
               twelve o'clock to hasten the <orgName role="Military">reinforcements</orgName>. <persName role="Admiral">The Admiral</persName> came in while I was
               over there, &amp; we saw <objectName key="Vehicles" role="Ship">the Cossack</objectName> go up afterwards I met <persName role="newspaper correspondent"
                         cert="high"
                         key="Fitzpatrick"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper123"
                         type="real">Fitzpatrick</persName>, cor.
               of Herald, who gave me <objectName key="Readable">papers</objectName> with the <objectName key="Readable">news</objectName> of the Battle of <placeName role="Battle site"
                          cert="high"
                          key="Winchester"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl094">Winchester</placeName>. He
               said the <orgName role="Military">17. Mass</orgName>. <orgName role="Military">103. N York</orgName>, &amp; <orgName role="Military">2 Maryland</orgName> were there - &amp; some
               <orgName key="Army">batteries</orgName> in all 3000. [Parke's?] Brigade with the companies New Jersey are at
               <placeName role="Fort"
                          key="Fort Macon"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl029">F Macon<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName>, so that we have of our old force, <orgName role="Military">25. 23. 27. 24. Mass</orgName>
               <orgName role="Military">10th 11th Conn</orgName>,
               <orgName role="Military">51st N.Y.</orgName>
               <orgName role="Military">57. Penna.</orgName>
               <orgName role="Military">21 Mass</orgName>, &amp; <orgName role="Military">4 companies 9th New Jersey</orgName>, <orgName role="Military">6 of the 48th Penna</orgName>, about 6000 effective men, &amp; the reinforcements 3000, 9000 in all. It
               is wonderful how the regiments are reduced by sickness and death. Our regiment
               for instance, had but 450 men on dress parade - &amp; say [200?] Guard &amp;
               other details make us a little over 500 strong. I have nineteen sick in my own
               company. But prospects of a battle would call the sick out. It appeared to be a
               matter of anxiety to <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
                         type="real">Gen Burnside</persName> that the troops were broken down so, and he
               attributed it partly to want of <objectName key="Food">fresh beef</objectName> &amp; <objectName key="Food">vegetables</objectName> &amp; he said that
               he had written to <placeName key="Washington N.C"
                          role="City"
                          cert="medium"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl090">Washington</placeName> urging <objectName key="Food">beef</objectName> to be sent. If the rebels wouldnt come
               for a week, they couldnt come past that <objectName key="Building">fort</objectName>. <persName key="Thomas Bell"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper072">Col. Bell</persName> says his orders are
               that if he hears heavy firing to form and march to <objectName key="Vehicle" type="Ship">the Ferry.</objectName>
               <persName key="Thomas Bell"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper072"
                         type="real">Lt Bell</persName> that was
               with <persName key="Capt. McRae"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper119">Capt. McRae</persName> in the battle with the <orgName role="Enemy forces">Texans</orgName> and <placeName role="Territory"
                          cert="high"
                          key="New Mexico"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl098">New Mexico<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName> was <persName>his brother</persName>.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary54.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date>April 2 Tuesday</date>
            </dateline>
            <p>
               <note anchored="true">Linn seems to have misdated this entry. In 1862 April 2nd fell on a Wednesday.</note>
               <name key="Positive" type="Weather">Bright and warm</name>. We were ordered out somewhere about nine or ten o'clock to go
               down &amp; receive the <orgName role="Military">2nd Maryland </orgName> &amp; marched to <placeName role="River">the river</placeName>, &amp; lay there
               until near one o'clock, when <persName key="Jesse Reno"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper086"
                         type="real">Gen. Reno</persName> reviewed us, &amp; told us to go back to
               <placeName role="Military camp">camp</placeName>. After the dress parade, we were ordered to move to <placeName role="Near the river">the other side of the river</placeName> in the morning. We have received 4 regts <orgName role="Military">103 &amp; 13 New York</orgName>, <orgName role="Military">2nd Maryland</orgName>
               &amp; <orgName role="Military">17 Mass</orgName>. We feel some regret about leaving our camp, now that we just been cleverly fixed. It is probable that the rebels have not more than 15.000 men at <placeName key="Kingston"
                          role="Town"
                          cert="high"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl048">Kingston<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName>, &amp; if they give us a few days, they can't faze us. <persName key="Charles Merrill"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper020"
                         type="real">Chas. Merrill</persName> &amp; <persName key="Warner"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper141"
                         type="real">Warner</persName> were promoted to Corporals today, and <persName key="Aaron Smith"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper006"
                         type="real">Aaron Smith</persName> to the vacant Serjeantry.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary54.jpg"/>
            <head>
               <date>Thursday 4th</date>
            </head>
            <p>
               <note anchored="true">Linn seems to have misdated this entry. In 1862 April 4th fell on a Friday.</note> Early this morning we unloaded the <objectName key="Equipment">baggage</objectName>, and got it on <objectName key="Nature">shore</objectName> about a quarter
               of a mile from <placeName role="Military camp">camp</placeName>. The <placeName role="Military camp">camp</placeName> is at <placeName role="Area of the town">the west end of the town.</placeName>
               <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary55.jpg"/>
               <orgName role="Military">The first Brigade</orgName> being all here except the <orgName role="Military">21st Mass</orgName> &amp; <orgName role="Military">2nd Maryland</orgName>, just in
               <placeName role="Fort">rear of the fort</placeName> that is in process of erection. It is a large one [?] near
               eight acres. The <objectName key="Building">western Bastions</objectName> are nearly completed <objectName key="Equipment">Cannon</objectName> are planted all
               along in the rear of it and in front of our camps. <persName key="Jesse Reno"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper086"
                         type="real">Gen Reno</persName> was here to see us
               this morning. The place is high &amp; <name key="Positive" type="Weather">dry</name> - but no doubt the <objectName key="Nature">sand</objectName> will prove a
               nuisance. About here the land is well cultivated, but the <objectName key="Equipment">fences</objectName> go down like
               [?] as each regiment comes in to encamp. Most of the day was spent getting our stores. It is pleasant to be here in a civilized place again. We
               received orders showing that the army is now divided into divisions two
               Brigades in <orgName role="Military">our Regiment</orgName>. We do not know how we are brigaded, but hope <persName key="John Hartranft"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper056"
                         type="real">Col. Hastraupt</persName> will have command of one Brigade. The difficulty rests in the fact
               that the date of his muster is junior to that of any other Colonel. Its absence now,
               too, may operate against him. <persName key="George Shorkley"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper002">Shorkley</persName> and I took a stroll <placeName role="Town center">down town</placeName>. It must
               be beautiful in the summer. Splendid <objectName key="Nature">trees</objectName> overarch every treet, the quaint
               <objectName key="Building">old houses</objectName>, giving one a feeling of satisfaction you do not experience, which
               seems a [word?], in fact, when you go into the handsome newly built northern
               towns. <objectName key="Nature">Peach trees</objectName> are loaded with <objectName key="Nature">blossoms</objectName>. Vegetation has commenced, and
               the <objectName key="Nature">buds</objectName> on the <objectName key="Nature">trees</objectName> are bursting.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary55.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date>Sunday April 6th</date>
            </dateline>
            <p>Yesterday and the day before we did little else than fix up our camp. We had a
               short Regimental drill in the afternoon. Our men have forgotten some but the
               ground was very rough. In the afternoon we were blessed with the arrival of a
               very large <objectName key="Readable">mail</objectName> from home. I received three <objectName key="Readable">letters</objectName> from <persName key="John Blair Linn"
                         role="Brother"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper051"
                         type="real">John</persName> &amp; 2 from
               <persName key="Annie Catherine Linn"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper015">Annie</persName> &amp; one from <persName key="Laura Sheller Linn"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper016"
                         type="real">Laura</persName>. The last one is dated March 31st, so it came
               through in five days. Both last evening and this evening, <persName key="Thomas Bell"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper072">Lt. Col. Bell</persName> and I took
               a stroll through <placeName>the quiet old town</placeName>. The streets are lined with high arching
               <objectName key="Nature">trees</objectName>, and the <objectName key="Nature">leaves</objectName> are just budding. There are many fine <objectName key="Equipment">houses</objectName>, but the
               beauty of them is in the large <objectName key="Nature">grounds</objectName> around them and the <objectName key="Nature">shrubbery</objectName>. <objectName key="Nature">Roses</objectName> are
               blooming, &amp; the <objectName key="Nature">lilac</objectName> &amp; <objectName key="Nature">locust</objectName> are out. The multiforce is crowded. It
               must be a charming place, and one could not help thinking of the pleasant
               social times they must have had in times past. There is wealth and leisure.
               Where <persName key="Capt. Ritchie"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper109"
                         type="real">Capt Ritchie</persName> has his quarters, was the office and <objectName key="Building">rooms</objectName> of a bachelor
               Lawyer, built in a cross shape, &amp; the Col tells me has every luxury of
               <objectName key="Building">library</objectName>, <objectName key="Building">office</objectName>, <objectName key="Building">bedroom</objectName>, <objectName key="Building">dining</objectName>[&amp;?] <objectName key="Building">bath</objectName> &amp;c. It was said that at his
               parties, he always refused to drink <objectName key="Drink">wine</objectName>, &amp; kept up the impression that he
               was temperate. His servant, whom <persName key="Capt. Ritchie"
                         role="Soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper109">Capt Ritchie</persName> has with him, on the Capt's
               observing a number of <objectName key="Drink">bottles</objectName> in a <objectName key="Furniture">closet</objectName> marked "[haregonic?]" that he would
               at times drink a bottle of it, 
               <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary56.jpg"/>
               <fw>
                  <date>April 6. continued.</date>
               </fw> and lie for a day or two, perfectly besotted. He
               was in that condition when the attack was made on <placeName role="Town"
                          cert="high"
                          key="New Berne"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl059">Newbern<precision match="@ref" precision="medium"/>
               </placeName>, &amp; had to be
               carried away. We had a company inspection in the forenoon. <persName key="Thomas Grier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper076"
                         type="real">Tom. Grier</persName> came and
               took dinner with us. <name key="Positive" type="Weather">The day was delightful</name>, &amp; we went up to the <objectName key="Furniture">platforms</objectName>
               &amp; one of the <objectName key="Furniture">curtains</objectName> is partially completed. I suppose that the alarms
               &amp; fuss last week was caused by a <persName key="Dr. Thompson"
                         role="Soldier Doctor"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper131"
                         type="real">Dr Thompson</persName> of <orgName role="Military">the First Brigade</orgName>, making a
               false alarm. <persName key="John Morris"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper057"
                         type="real">Morris</persName> said he had bought about <objectName key="Nature">70 bales of cotton</objectName> of an old
               fellow out in the country, and after he had paid the money, some rebel cavalry
               came down and burnt it. An order was read on dress parade last night, sending
               the doctor to report at <placeName key="Washington N.C"
                          role="City"
                          cert="medium"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl090">Washington<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName> with the recommendation to the Secretary of
               War to dismiss him from service - that soldiers lost enough rest &amp; sleep
               not to be annoyed by false alarms and that all alarmists would be dealt
               summarily with. We formed under arms and marched into <placeName role="Church">the Presbyterian church</placeName>,
               where <persName key="Charles Mallory"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper019">Mr Mallory</persName> preached. We also heard a part of the grand concert given by
               <orgName role="Music">the 24th Mass Band</orgName>, Gilmore's in front of <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
                         type="real">Gen. Burnsides</persName> headquarters. After we
               got back we found all our men from <placeName role="Island"
                          key="Roanoke Island"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl076">Roanoke Island<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName> had gotten back except <persName key="Murphy"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper140"
                         type="real">Murphy</persName>
               &amp; <persName key="Adam Henry"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper010"
                         type="real">Adam Henry</persName>, who have lymphoid fever. We look very red &amp; some will be
               marked. Poor <persName key="James A. Kelley"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper045">Jim Kelly</persName> died on the 27th of March - he was delirious for 8 days
               and swore like a trooper until he died. It was owing to his impudence stripping
               stark naked - he was so selfruled they could not get him to take any care of
               himself. His side on which he lay was completely rotten - in fact he was one
               mass of corruption. I am glad the rest have gotten over it so happily. We have two cases on <placeName role="Across the river">the other side of the river</placeName>. We heard, through <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
                         type="real">Gen Burnsides</persName>
               spies, who have just returned from <placeName role="Town"
                          cert="high"
                          key="Suffolk, Virginia"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl082">Suffolk<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName>, that <persName key="Samuel P. Heintzelman"
                         role="soldier"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper069">Gen. Heintzelman</persName> had taken
               <placeName role="Town"
                          key="Yorktown, Virginia"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl096">Yorktown</placeName> with <objectName key="Equipment">180 pieces of cannon</objectName>. Our friends in the North appear to have
               been uneasy about us, for fear that we would get caught in a trap. <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
                         type="real">Gen. Burnside</persName> has been kept thoroughly informed of everything that has taken place.
               His spies are everywhere, &amp; he has a very finely organized system. Many are
               <orgName role="Intelligence">New York detectives</orgName>. Six of them were on board <objectName key="Vehicle">the Cossack</objectName>, &amp; it was a long
               time before we knew who they were. They appeared and disappeared - where we
               never saw. One I remember did not come on board for a long time, when the
               morning we left <placeName role="Base"
                          cert="low"
                          key="Hatteras Inlet"
                          ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl045">Hatteras<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/>
               </placeName> to come here, he suddenly turned up. You would take
               him for a Jersey huckster rather than a detective. We were on board a week with
               them when we had <orgName role="Prisoners">the prisoners</orgName>. We kept the prisoners below except at certain
               hours, when the detectives would stay in their rooms. 
               <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary57.jpg"/>
               <fw>
                  <date>April 6 continued.</date>
               </fw> It is wonderful that the change in the appointment of
               <persName role="Military">Corporal</persName> has made on <persName key="Charles Merrill"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper020"
                         type="real">Charles Merrill</persName>. He is dressed very neatly and his <objectName key="Body">hair</objectName>
               and <objectName key="Body">beard</objectName> are nicely trimmed, and he appears to feel for the first time in his life
               that he has some responsibility. He does his work carefully and intelligently,
               &amp; takes a great interest in it.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary57.jpg"/>
            <head>
               <date>Monday 7.</date>
            </head>
            <p>It was <name key="Positive" type="Weather">bright fine summer morning</name> but <name key="Negetive" type="Weather">commenced raining</name> about <time>twelve o'clock</time>,
               &amp; <name key="Negetive" type="Weather">rained</name>
               <time>until evening</time>. We had a regimental roll call, &amp; company drill. I
               spent most of the day writing <objectName key="Readable">letters</objectName> to <persName key="John Blair Linn"
                         role="Brother"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper051"
                         type="real">John</persName> &amp; <persName key="Louisa">Louisa</persName> &amp; one to <persName role="Jim Kelly's wife">Jim Kelly's wife</persName>. This evening <persName key="Jacob G. Beaver"
                         role="Soldier"
                         cert="high"
                         ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper003"
                         type="real">Beaver</persName> and I shot <placeName role="Town center">down town</placeName>. It was very
               desolate. The [sandy]? evil drinks in the rain as fast as it falls. It looked
               odd to see the <name key="Negetive" type="Weather">rain come pouring down</name>, &amp; sort of melt away like snow.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
